  "prompt": "So, is it illegal to launder money?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is illegal in virtually every country around the world. It is a criminal offense that involves disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions. The goal is to make the money appear as though it comes from a legitimate source.\n\nIn the United States, for example, money laundering is prohibited under the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)** and the **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986**. Penalties for money laundering can include substantial fines, asset forfeiture, and lengthy prison sentences\u2014up to 20 years or more per offense, depending on the circumstances.\n\nInternationally, efforts to combat money laundering are coordinated through organizations like the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**, which sets global standards for anti-money laundering (AML) and counter-terrorist financing (CFT) measures. Many countries have implemented laws and regulations to comply with these standards.\n\nIf you suspect or are involved in money laundering, it is strongly advised to seek legal counsel immediately.",
